Colombian President Petro Petro said earlier that he had angered Trump by refusing to allow a U.S. military plane carrying deported immigrants to land. 
Subsequently, Trump ordered a 25% emergency tariff on Colombian government officials "and all allies and supporters", which would increase to 50% within a week. He also announced the immediate revocation of visas for Colombian government officials and the president's "supporters", and Colombian citizens would be subject to stricter scrutiny at U.S. airports. 
The White House said on Sunday (January 26) that Colombia had made concessions and agreed to accept citizens repatriated on civilian aircraft after Trump threatened to impose major sanctions.

name: 李老师不是你老师
content: Pediatric surgeon Pei Honggang wrote: In 2024, the Medical Insurance Bureau will add 91 new drugs for centralized procurement, including 11 Chinese patent medicines and 19 Chinese medicine injections. So many useless or even harmful drugs can be approved by the medical insurance and drug departments and enter the centralized procurement. The entire bowl of centralized procurement is like a bowl of rice, and you can see rat droppings on the surface without turning it over. How can people believe which rice grains are good? To put it bluntly, there is no standard for filtering rat droppings. It is too early to discuss which rice is good and which is bad.

Recently, the fact that the quality of generic drugs purchased in the centralized procurement and the evaluation data of generic drugs are the same has caused heated discussions.
Li Qing, a nephrologist at Tianjin Teda Hospital, said that it is also a scientific spirit to avoid data editing errors. The double-blind experimental results of the lipid-lowering drug "rosuvastatin" showed that the drug would cause kidney function to decline, but the company did not destroy or modify the data, but published the research results. In the end, the drug was not only not abandoned, but was welcomed for its good lipid-lowering effect. https://pbs.twimg.com/ext_tw_video_thumb/1883820268260601856/pu/img/0SGXP32c8aVjx_wS.jpg

name: 李老师不是你老师
content:
NYT: China cracks down on 'panda fan clubs', bans 'extreme fan culture' The government is asking panda fans to be careful about what they say and do online, and police are targeting those who advocate for animal welfare or criticize overseas exchanges (such as bringing pandas to Washington). Some internet celebrities have been arrested or questioned for what authorities call "rumors" and "extreme fan culture."
In an effort to control online culture, Xi Jinping has launched a war on online fans, likening fan clubs to "cults." Authorities have detained sports fans who smear Chinese athletes, arrested people who swarmed airports to greet celebrities, and suspended the accounts of K-pop fans.
"These civilian 'patriots' are sometimes encouraged or tolerated by the government," said Xiao Qiang, an internet freedom researcher at the University of California, Berkeley. "But when the official narrative has new demands, panda fans can also be punished and arrested."
